# AeroLIT PXE Content Bundle Layout, Status, and Troubleshooting

This document explains how the PXE content image fits into an AeroLIT bundle, what the generated status files mean, and how to troubleshoot common problems.

The goal is to help someone verify the image and generated PXE content before testing with real PXE hardware.

## Expected bundle layout

A typical AeroLIT offline bundle may look like this:

```text
bootstrap.sh
collections-hub/
extracted_isos/
files/
repos/
```

The PXE content image normally fits under `files/pxe/`:

```text
files/
  pxe/
    pxe-content.tar
```

Extracted RHEL ISO trees usually live under `extracted_isos/`:

```text
extracted_isos/
  rhel8iso/
  rhel9iso/
  rhel10iso/
```

RHEL 7 is supported by the generator, but it is not the main AeroLIT target. If needed, use:

```text
extracted_isos/
  rhel7iso/
```

## ISO tree requirements

A detected ISO tree must include PXE boot files:

```text
images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
images/pxeboot/initrd.img
```

For RHEL 8, 9, and 10, the extracted ISO tree should also include:

```text
BaseOS/repodata/repomd.xml
AppStream/repodata/repomd.xml
```

For RHEL 7, the extracted ISO tree should include:

```text
repodata/repomd.xml
```

If `vmlinuz` or `initrd.img` is missing, the ISO tree is not detected.

If repository metadata is missing, the ISO tree may still be detected, but validation reports a warning because installs may fail after boot.

## Container path mapping

The generator uses container paths. The default paths are:

```text
/iso                  extracted ISO trees
/overrides            user/site customizations
/templates            built-in templates
/profiles             built-in profiles
/etc/nginx/html       generated web root
```

A normal run maps host bundle content into those container paths.

Example:

```bash
podman run --rm -d \
  --name pxe-content \
  -p 18080:8080 \
  -e PXE_SERVER=<pxe-server-ip-or-hostname> \
  -e PXE_PORT=18080 \
  -v /bundle/extracted_isos:/iso:Z \
  -v /bundle/files/pxe/overrides:/overrides:Z \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:latest
```

## Generated files

The image generates content under the web root.

| Path | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `/boot.ipxe` | Main iPXE menu |
| `/ks/*.ks` | Generated Kickstart files |
| `/index.html` | Simple browser status page |
| `/generated/status.json` | Machine-readable status and validation report |
| `/generated/status.txt` | Human-readable status report |
| `/generated/isos.txt` | Detected ISO inventory |
| `/generated/kickstart-state/` | Hash state used to detect manual `/ks` edits |
| `/generated/preserved-kickstarts/` | Candidate regenerated files when manual edits are preserved |

## Status files

Use these first when troubleshooting:

```text
/generated/status.txt
/generated/status.json
```

`status.txt` is easiest for humans.

`status.json` is best for automation, test scripts, and exact troubleshooting.

Important `status.json` sections:

| Section | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `validation_summary` | Overall health, total checks, warnings, and errors |
| `validation_results` | Full list of validation checks |
| `boot_artifact_validation` | Checks related to `boot.ipxe` and boot target references |
| `detected_isos` | ISO trees discovered by the generator |
| `repo_validation` | Repository metadata checks for each detected ISO |
| `profiles` | Visible PXE profile definitions |
| `generated_kickstarts` | Kickstart files generated for implemented profiles |
| `active_overrides` | Override profile/template files that were detected |
| `stale_kickstarts` | Old generated Kickstarts that were deleted or preserved |

## Validation failure policy

The generator validates generated content after rendering.

Set policy with:

```text
PXE_VALIDATION_FAILURE_POLICY=warn
PXE_VALIDATION_FAILURE_POLICY=fail
```

### `warn`

This is the default.

The generator writes the content and reports validation problems in status files, but it does not exit failed.

Use this when you want the server to stay up while you troubleshoot.

### `fail`

The generator writes status files, then exits non-zero if validation errors exist.

Use this in CI, test scripts, and merge-request validation.

Warnings do not fail generation. Only validation errors fail when policy is `fail`.

## Manual `/ks` edit policy

Generated Kickstarts live under:

```text
/ks
```

The preferred customization path is still overrides:

```text
/overrides/profiles
/overrides/templates
```

Manual edits under `/ks` are the emergency path.

Set policy with:

```text
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=preserve
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=overwrite
```

### `preserve`

This is the default.

If a generated Kickstart was manually edited, the generator preserves the edited `/ks` file and writes the newly regenerated version as a candidate under:

```text
/generated/preserved-kickstarts/
```

### `overwrite`

The generator replaces manual edits under `/ks` with the newly generated version.

Use this when you want generated content to return to a clean, repeatable state.

## Known RHEL differences

| Version | PXE support in current definitions | Repo layout | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| RHEL 7 | BIOS enabled, UEFI disabled | single repo metadata under `repodata/` | Older layout; not the main AeroLIT target |
| RHEL 8 | UEFI and BIOS enabled | `BaseOS` and `AppStream` | Good baseline for legacy and UEFI testing |
| RHEL 9 | UEFI enabled, BIOS disabled | `BaseOS` and `AppStream` | Primary modern target |
| RHEL 10 | UEFI enabled, BIOS disabled | `BaseOS` and `AppStream` | Future/current target depending on site readiness |

The generator only detects extracted ISO trees that match the configured directory names and contain the required PXE boot files.

## Testing without real PXE hardware

The built-in image test runner can validate most image behavior without DHCP, TFTP, Foreman, or a physical PXE client.

Run:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

This creates fake ISO trees, generates PXE content, starts temporary Nginx where needed, and confirms generated HTTP paths work.

Passing tests prove the image-generated content is healthy. They do not prove a specific network, DHCP scope, firewall path, or physical machine firmware setting is correct.

## Troubleshooting

### No ISOs are detected

Check that the mounted ISO root contains the expected directory names:

```text
rhel7iso
rhel8iso
rhel9iso
rhel10iso
```

Then check for:

```text
images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
images/pxeboot/initrd.img
```

Also confirm the container can see the files:

```bash
podman exec pxe-content ls -l /iso
podman exec pxe-content find /iso -path '*/images/pxeboot/*' -maxdepth 5 -type f
```

### ISO is detected, but install fails after boot

The boot files may exist, but repo content may be incomplete.

Check `repo_validation` in:

```text
/generated/status.json
```

For RHEL 8, 9, and 10, confirm:

```text
BaseOS/repodata/repomd.xml
AppStream/repodata/repomd.xml
```

### `boot.ipxe` is missing

Run the generator manually inside the container and check the error:

```bash
podman exec pxe-content python3 /usr/local/bin/generate-pxe-content.py --once
```

Common causes:

- `PXE_SERVER` is not set
- invalid profile YAML
- missing template referenced by an implemented profile
- Jinja rendering error

### A profile appears but has no real install target

That is expected for placeholder profiles.

A profile only generates real boot targets when:

```yaml
implemented: true
```

Placeholder profiles can appear in the menu without generating real `inst.ks=` boot entries.

### Override profile is not being used

Check that the override file is under:

```text
/overrides/profiles/*.yml
/overrides/profiles/*.yaml
```

Then check `active_overrides` and `profiles` in:

```text
/generated/status.json
```

An override profile with the same `profile_id` replaces the base profile.

### Override template is not being used

Check that the profile points to the expected template:

```yaml
kickstart_template: ks/rhel8-example.ks.j2
```

Then place the override template at:

```text
/overrides/templates/ks/rhel8-example.ks.j2
```

Check `template_source_detail` under `generated_kickstarts` in `status.json`.

Expected value when override wins:

```json
"template_source_detail": "override"
```

### Jinja include fails

Use quoted include paths:

```jinja
{% include "partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2" %}
```

The partial path must exist under the built-in or override template root.

Built-in partials are under:

```text
templates/partials/
```

Override partials can be added under:

```text
/overrides/templates/partials/
```

### Manual `/ks` edit will not go away

The default policy preserves manual edits.

To force regeneration over manual edits, run with:

```text
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=overwrite
```

Then regenerate.

### Status health is warning

Warnings usually mean content may still work, but something should be reviewed.

Common warning:

```text
repository metadata is missing
```

This means the ISO tree has boot files, but install repo content may be incomplete.

### Status health is error

Errors mean generated content is structurally wrong.

Common errors:

- missing `boot.ipxe`
- empty Kickstart
- unresolved Jinja block
- unresolved Jinja variable
- generated boot target missing
- generated Kickstart missing

Open:

```text
/generated/status.txt
```

Then review the `Validation Results` section.

### HTTP works, but PXE boot does not

The image only serves HTTP content. Real PXE boot also depends on network configuration.

Check:

- DHCP scope
- IP helper settings
- firewall rules
- route between PXE client and server
- firmware mode, UEFI vs BIOS
- iPXE chain URL
- client can reach `http://<server>:<port>/boot.ipxe`

### Browser can open `/boot.ipxe`, but install fails

Check the URLs inside `boot.ipxe`:

```bash
curl http://<server>:18080/boot.ipxe
```

Then test the referenced files directly:

```text
/rhel8/images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
/rhel8/images/pxeboot/initrd.img
/ks/rhel8-minimal.ks
/rhel8/BaseOS/repodata/repomd.xml
/rhel8/AppStream/repodata/repomd.xml
```

### Root password hash concern

Set a site-specific hash with:

```text
ROOTPW_HASH=<sha512-crypt-hash>
```

The default hash exists for lab/bootstrap testing. Do not rely on it for real environments.

Status files should not expose the root password hash.

## Quick pre-merge checklist

Before merging an image or generator change:

1. Build and push the `:test` image.
2. Run the built-in tests:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

3. Confirm these pass:

```text
Basic image test passed
Overrides and preserve policy test passed
Validation / health policy test passed
```

4. Confirm the pipeline is green.
5. Merge when the MR changes match the intended scope.